The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;scattering of light&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;

&lt;div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The bluish colour of water in deep sea is due to the &lt;strong&gt;scattering of light&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When sunlight enters the sea, it is scattered by the water molecules and particles in the water.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;shorter wavelengths of light (blue and violet) are scattered more&lt;/strong&gt; compared to the longer wavelengths (red, yellow, etc.), making the deep sea appear blue.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This phenomenon is similar to why the sky appears blue during the day.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Light scattering is a process where light is forced to deviate from a straight trajectory due to non-uniformities in the medium through which it passes.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The phenomenon is studied under the branch of physics known as optics.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;Rayleigh scattering&lt;/strong&gt; is more effective at short wavelengths, which is why blue light is scattered more in water.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Other factors such as water purity and presence of other substances can also affect the color perceived.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

